	<h1>Propositional logic 2</h1>
	<h4>Extended truth tables</h4>

	<p>Erik Hoversten</p>
	<p>Rutgers university: LRP, fall 2014</p>
	<p>October 27, 2014</p>
</section>

<section>
	<section>
	
		<h2>Truth tables</h2>
		<p>The meaning of propositions</p>

		<ul>
			<li class="fragment">In propositional logic, the complete meaning of a proposition is given by its truth table</li>
			<li class="fragment">This is because the truth table shows all the possible situations across which the formula's truth value can vary.
			<ul>
				<li class="fragment">Thus, it gives the <em>truth conditions</em> for that formula.</li>
			</ul></li>
		</ul>
	</section>

<section>
<h2 id="basic-prop">Basic propositions</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Let's call the formulas that we can form through the simplest application of the syntax rules the <strong>basic propositions</strong>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">These propositions contain <strong>no more than 1</strong> connective.
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Basic propositions in our language:
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Atomic propositions</li>
<li class="fragment">Negations</li>
<li class="fragment">Conjunctions</li>
<li class="fragment">Disjunctions</li>
<li class="fragment">Conditionals</li>
<li class="fragment">Biconditionals</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
