	<section>
<h2 id="complex-prop">Complex propositions</h2>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Let's call any WFF that is built from multiple applications of the syntax rules a <strong>complex proposition</strong>.
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Complex propositions contain <strong>at least 2</strong> connectives.</li>
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Complex propositions are built up <strong>recursively</strong> from basic propositions.
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Thus, we can construct the truth table for a complex proposition by putting together truth tables of basic propositions.
</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Examples:
<ul>
<li class="fragment">(A &#x2219; B) &#x2228; (E &#x2283; F)</li>
<li class="fragment">(~A &#x2228; ~B)</li>
<li class="fragment">~(A &#x2261; B) &#x2283; C</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>
</section>

<section>
	<section>
<h2>Complex truth tables</h2>
<p>Construct the columns</p>

<ul>
<li class="fragment">Add a column for every distinct propositional variable occurring in the WFF</li>
<li class="fragment">Add a column for every distinct basic proposition occurring in the WFF.
<ul>Start with the smallest propositions and work your way out.</ul></li>
<li class="fragment">Add a column for the complete WFF</li>
<li class="fragment">Example: </li>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">~(A &#x2261; B) &#x2283; C</li>
</ul>
</ul>

<table class="fragment">
<thead>
	<td>p</td>
	<td>q</td>
	<td>r</td>
	<td class="fragment">(p &#x2261; q)</td>
	<td class="fragment">~(p &#x2261; q)</td>
	<td class="fragment">~(p &#x2261; q) &#x2283; r</td>
</thead>
<tbody>
</tbody>
</table>

	</section>
	
	<section>
<h2 id="vocabulary">Complex truth tables</h2>
<p>Construct the rows</p>

<ul>
<li class="fragment">Ensure you have all possible combinations of truth values for the WFF. (2<sup>n</sup> rule)</li>
<li class="fragment"> Fill the columns for propositional variables. (divide by 2 rule)</li>
</ul>

<table class="fragment">
<thead>
	<td>p</td>
	<td>q</td>
	<td>r</td>
	<td>(p &#x2261; q)</td>
	<td>~(p &#x2261; q)</td>
	<td>~(p &#x2261; q) &#x2283; r</td>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>T</td><td>T</td><td>T</td></tr>
<tr><td>T</td><td>T</td><td>F</td></tr>
<tr><td>T</td><td>F</td><td>T</td></tr>
<tr><td>T</td><td>F</td><td>F</td></tr>
<tr><td>F</td><td>T</td><td>T</td></tr>
<tr><td>F</td><td>T</td><td>F</td></tr>
<tr><td>F</td><td>F</td><td>T</td></tr>
<tr><td>F</td><td>F</td><td>F</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

	</section>

	<section>
<h2 id="syntax">Complex truth tables</h2>
<p>Fill the rows</p>
<ul>
<li class="fragment">Fill the columns for the basic propositions using the truth tables we constructed above.
<li class="fragment">Then treat those basic propositions as individual propositional variables when they occur in other columns</li>
<li class="fragment">Fill the columns for complex propositions using the columns you already filled for the basic propositions contained in them.</li>
<li class="fragment">Continue this process until all the columns are filled.</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
	</section>
	
	<section>
<h2 id="syntax">Complex truth tables</h2>
<p>Complete example: ~(p &#x2261; q) &#x2283; r</p>

<table class="fragment">
<thead>
	<td>p</td>
	<td>q</td>
	<td>r</td>
	<td>(p &#x2261; q)</td>
	<td>~(p &#x2261; q)</td>
	<td>~(p &#x2261; q) &#x2283; r</td>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>T</td><td>T</td><td>T</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
<tr><td>T</td><td>T</td><td>F</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
<tr><td>T</td><td>F</td><td>T</td>
	<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
<tr><td>T</td><td>F</td><td>F</td>
	<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F</td></td>
<tr><td>F</td><td>T</td><td>T</td>
	<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
<tr><td>F</td><td>T</td><td>F</td>
	<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F</td></td>
<tr><td>F</td><td>F</td><td>T</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
<tr><td>F</td><td>F</td><td>F</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
</tr></tr></tr></tr></tr></tr></tr></tr>
</tbody>
</table>
	
</section>

<section>
<h2 id="syntax">Complex truth tables</h2>
<p>Complete example: (p &#x2283; q) &#x2219; (q &#x2283; p)</p>

<table class="fragment">
<thead>
	<td>p</td>
	<td>q</td>
	<td>p &#x2283; q</td>
	<td>q &#x2283; p</td>
	<td>(p &#x2283; q) &#x2219; (q &#x2283; p)</td>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td>T</td><td>T</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
<tr><td>T</td><td>F</td>
	<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F</td></td>
<tr><td>F</td><td>T</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">F<td class="fragment">F</td></td>
<tr><td>F</td><td>F</td>
	<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">T<td class="fragment">T</td></td>
</tr></tr></tr></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p class="fragment">Notice that this table is identical to the table for the biconditional. This shows that <strong>(p &#x2283; q) &#x2219; (q &#x2283; p)</strong> means the same thing as <strong>p &#x2261; q</strong></p>
	
</section>
</section>